For smaller values of `n`, this implementation is concise and easy to understand. However, for larger `n` (e.g., `n > 40`), consider using a memoized or iterative approach to avoid performance issues. Here's an optimized version using memoization:
```
int fibonacci(int n, std::vector<int>& memo) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    if (memo[n] != -1) return memo[n];
    memo[n] = fibonacci(n-1, memo) + fibonacci(n-2, memo);
    return memo[n];
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter a positive integer n: ";
    std::cin >> n;
    if (n < 0) {
        std::cerr << "Error: n must be a positive integer.\n";
        return 1;
    }
    std::vector<int> memo(n+1, -1); // -1 indicates uninitialized
    int result = fibonacci(n, memo);
    std::cout << "F(" << n << ") = " << result << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This version uses a `std::vector` to cache `F(i)` values, reducing the time complexity to O(n) and making it suitable for larger `n`. You can further optimize this by using an iterative approach with a simple loop, eliminating recursion altogether. For example:
```
int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    int a = 0, b = 1, result;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {
        result = a + b;
        a = b;
        b = result;
    }
    return result;
}
```
This iterative approach is concise, efficient (O(n)), and avoids recursion and memoization. It's a good choice for computing large Fibonacci numbers. Choose the implementation that best fits your specific use case and performance requirements.

